A process can opt out of THP for its whole address space with
prctl(PR_SET_THP_DISABLE), but there is no per-process opt *in*: no
way to say "treat every THP-eligible anonymous VMA in this mm as if
MADV_HUGEPAGE had been called on it" without either modifying the
program or flipping the system-wide policy to enabled=always /
defrag=always for everyone.

Commit 9dc21bbd62ed ("prctl: extend PR_SET_THP_DISABLE to optionally
exclude VM_HUGEPAGE") turned PR_SET_THP_DISABLE into a flags
interface and named this exact use case as its scenario (4): "Stay at
'madvise' system policy, but enable THPs even when not advised for
selected workloads -- 'always' policy."  It also stated that "we're
not willing to add completely new toggles".  This series follows that
direction instead of fighting it: no new prctl numbers and no new
toggle.  Patch 1 adds the enable-side flag, PR_THP_ALWAYS_ADVISED,
to the same PR_SET_THP_DISABLE flags interface; patch 2 adds the
khugepaged promptness needed to make the flag actually deliver.

Interface summary
=================

  prctl(PR_SET_THP_DISABLE, 0, PR_THP_ALWAYS_ADVISED, 0, 0)
    THPs not disabled; additionally treat every THP-eligible
    anonymous VMA as if MADV_HUGEPAGE had been called on it
    (eligibility under global "madvise", defrag=always allocation
    effort).  Inherited across fork()/exec().  64-bit only.

  prctl(PR_SET_THP_DISABLE, 0, 0, 0, 0)
    Back to default: clears the disable modes (as before) and the
    always-advised hint.  No behaviour change for existing callers.

  prctl(PR_SET_THP_DISABLE, 1, [PR_THP_DISABLE_EXCEPT_ADVISED], 0, 0)
    Disable modes, unchanged -- and additionally clear the
    always-advised hint: disable always wins.  Combining arg2 != 0
    with PR_THP_ALWAYS_ADVISED fails with -EINVAL (mutually
    exclusive by construction).

  prctl(PR_GET_THP_DISABLE, 0, 0, 0, 0)
    0 = default, 1 = disabled completely, 3 = disabled except
    advised (all as before), 4 = PR_THP_ALWAYS_ADVISED set (bit 0
    stays the "is disabled" bit, matching the "1 | flags" encoding
    9dc21bbd62ed reserved).

Motivation
==========

The concrete use case is a game launcher (Steam, gamescope, or a
five-line wrapper) opting in a third-party game binary that cannot be
modified to madvise its own heap.  Profiling Factorio 2.0 headless on
a Steam Deck (Van Gogh APU) showed a memory/TLB-bound update loop:

  - IPC 0.38, dTLB-load-misses 73.4% of dTLB loads;
  - only 18.5% of the 154 MB anon heap hugepage-backed (28.6 MB
    AnonHugePages) under the stock enabled=madvise policy, because
    the game's allocator never issues MADV_HUGEPAGE;
  - setting the global THP knobs to aggressive drops dTLB-load-misses
    to 22.8% (52x fewer absolute misses) and ran the benchmark ~10%
    faster in an exploratory single-shot probe of that broader global
    configuration (uncontrolled; the controlled interleaved
    aggressive-khugepaged A/B below puts the ceiling at +5.76%) --
    proving heap TLB pressure is the lever, but a global knob imposes
    synchronous-compaction latency on every process on the system,
    which is exactly why the kernel default is madvise.

With the series applied and only the target process flagged (stock
global khugepaged tunables, global enabled=madvise), an interleaved
A/B on the Deck measured +2.53% updates-per-second (ms/tick 1.4808 ->
1.4443; Welch t=5.79, p<0.0001, n=32/side interleaved; the UPS gain
is the ratio of mean ms/tick).  No interleaved ON block mean was
worse than the overall OFF mean.  A global aggressive-khugepaged
configuration puts the ceiling at +5.76% UPS (ms/tick 1.4853 ->
1.4044, n=18/side); the honest gap analysis is in patch 2.

Additional measurement (2026-07-17, supporting): a second real game
shows the same binding constraint.  Civilization VI's first-party AI
benchmark on a Steam Deck (stock SteamOS 6.16 kernel, global THP
enabled=always) was A/B'd on khugepaged promptness alone via sysfs --
stock scan_sleep_millisecs=10000 / pages_to_scan=4096 vs prompt
100 / 16384 -- interleaved, 3 blocks x 2 reps per arm, with the
prompt arm running later in the session and therefore thermally
disadvantaged.  Frame-time results: fps_avg +4.2% (Welch t=20.4),
1%-low fps +4.2%, frame-time p99 -6.3%, the same sign in all three
blocks.  To be clear about what this probes: global khugepaged
promptness under enabled=always, not the per-mm mechanism of this
series.  It demonstrates that khugepaged collapse latency is a
binding constraint for a second real game heap, which is exactly
what motivates per-process promptness without global tuning.

Why the obvious alternatives do not work
========================================

The emulation blessed by 9dc21bbd62ed -- handle scenario (4) through
(3), i.e. set the global policy to "always" and have everything that
should stay at "madvise" opt out via PR_THP_DISABLE_EXCEPT_ADVISED --
is backwards for this deployment shape.  On a handheld or fleet node
where exactly one process should be elevated, it requires modifying
every OTHER process on the system to opt out: init, system daemons,
third-party services -- most of which cannot be modified, which is
the very premise that motivates a prctl in the first place.  The
natural encoding of "one process opts in" is a flag on that one
process.

The BPF-based per-process THP policy direction that 9dc21bbd62ed
pointed to as the likely future was subsequently set aside: per LWN's
coverage of the LSFMM+BPF 2026 discussion ("Controlling memory
management with BPF", https://lwn.net/Articles/1072538/), the
THP-policy BPF direction was set aside, so there is no imminent
replacement interface for this flag to collide with.

MADV_HUGEPAGE from the app or loader: the binary is third-party and
cannot be changed.  An LD_PRELOAD shim would have to interpose every
allocator path and re-advise each new mapping; it is fragile,
per-allocation, and cannot cover mappings the process creates later.
(An LD_PRELOAD constructor issuing a single prctl, by contrast, is
the exact mechanism used for the measurements here.)

process_madvise() from a wrapper: process_madvise_remote_valid()
deliberately allows only MADV_COLD, MADV_PAGEOUT, MADV_WILLNEED and
MADV_COLLAPSE on a remote mm; MADV_HUGEPAGE cannot be applied
remotely.  Extending process_madvise() to allow remote MADV_HUGEPAGE
would not close the gap either: the advice is per-VMA and does
persist for the VMAs it hits, but it only reaches VMAs that exist at
advise time -- every new VMA the process creates afterwards (a
growing heap's fresh allocator arenas) starts unadvised, and a
supervisor cannot re-advise on every mmap().  MADV_COLLAPSE is
one-shot in the same way: it collapses what exists at the time of the
call and does nothing for the future faults of a growing heap, which
is where most of this workload's heap comes from.

RSS / memory footprint
======================

The standard objection to whole-mm advise is RSS bloat: khugepaged
collapse at the default max_ptes_none (511) can fill in almost-empty
PMDs, inflating RSS on sparse heaps.  That risk is real and this
series does not pretend otherwise.  What the flag does NOT do is
change collapse policy: max_ptes_none and the mTHP-era collapse
limits apply to a flagged mm unchanged, exactly as they would if the
process had issued madvise(MADV_HUGEPAGE) itself.  The opt-in is
per-process and made by a supervisor that owns the memory/performance
trade-off on the target device (the measured deployment is a 16 GB
UMA handheld running one foreground game).  The THP shrinker (6.12)
reclaims underused THPs system-wide, flagged mms included, and any
future global anti-bloat control applies to flagged mms identically,
since they go through the same fault and collapse paths as advised
ones.

Series structure
================

Patch 1 adds the UAPI flag, the mm flag, fault-path eligibility and
GFP treatment, fork/exec inheritance, and documentation.  It is fully
functional on its own, and it is also -- by our own measurement --
neutral on its own: on-fault THP only covers post-flag faults, and
stock khugepaged (10 s scans, small round-robin budget) never caught
up with the already-faulted heap within a benchmark run.

Patch 2 makes khugepaged collapse flagged mms promptly (registration
kick on opt-in, per-mm scan-budget boost, sleep-skip while a flagged
mm is actively collapsing).  All three mechanisms are keyed on the
flag from patch 1 and are exactly zero-cost when no process opts in.
This patch is what turns the neutral flag into the measured +2.53%.

Notes for reviewers
===================

- The hint deliberately does NOT count as "advised" for
  PR_THP_DISABLE_EXCEPT_ADVISED, and setting any disable mode clears
  it: disable always wins, and PR_GET_THP_DISABLE always reports a
  single coherent state.  Per-VMA MADV_NOHUGEPAGE and global "never"
  also still win.
- GET encoding: we return PR_THP_ALWAYS_ADVISED (4, bit 0 clear)
  when the hint is set.  0 still means "pure default" and "value & 1"
  remains the "is disabled" test.  A legacy caller testing the whole
  value != 0 can only be confused inside a process that itself (or
  whose launcher) opted in; processes not using the new flag see
  bit-for-bit unchanged values.  Reasoning spelled out in patch 1.
- The feature is anon-only (gated in the vma_thp_always() helper, so
  the eligibility and gfp-mask consumers see the same scope), 64-bit
  only, default-off.  The 64-bit gate is a policy choice, not a
  mechanical constraint (NUM_MM_FLAG_BITS is 64 everywhere): no
  identified 32-bit use case and untested there, and rejecting the
  flag today is relaxable later without breaking UAPI, whereas the
  reverse is not.
- Selftests extending tools/testing/selftests/mm/prctl_thp_disable.c
  to cover the enable-side flag will accompany the non-RFC posting.

Measurements were taken on a 6.16.12-valve24.4 (Steam Deck) kernel
carrying an equivalent backport of this series with a prototype prctl
spelling and pre-mTHP khugepaged; this port to the current tree
(PR_SET_THP_DISABLE flags interface, mm_flags_t bitmap API, explicit
inheritance in mm_init(), and khugepaged's mTHP collapse support
taken into account) is build-tested on x86_64 and i386 (PAE) but not
yet re-measured.  The series applies on v7.2-rc3; it will be rebased
to mm-new for the non-RFC posting.

